The user is asking about lib.rs. Let me check what we defined in the project structure vs what was actually written.

In the project structure we defined:
```
[lib]
name = "neo_core"
path = "src/lib.rs"
```

But in the lib.rs I wrote, it re-declares all the modules:
```rust
pub mod types;
pub mod core;
pub mod parser;
pub mod ai;
pub mod agent;
```

But main.rs ALSO declares these modules:
```rust
mod types;
mod core;
mod parser;
mod ai;
mod agent;
mod cli;


```

I see the issue now - both lib.rs and main.rs are declaring the same modules, which creates duplication. The correct approach in Rust is to declare modules once in lib.rs and have main.rs import from the library instead. Let me fix this by removing the module declarations from main.rs and using the library imports properly.

```

rust
use neo_core::{types, core, parser, ai, agent, EntryPoint, NeoError};
```

This way main.rs imports everything it needs from the lib crate instead of redeclaring modules. The cli module stays in main.rs since it's binary-specific, but all the shared logic comes from lib.rs through the use statement.

